content:
 One of my favorite simple pleasures in life is to walk into a moderately populated bar (enough people to be lively, but not so much as to be chaotic) and order a Tom Collins. A little while ago I asked an older friend of mine if they often made them while bartending in the 90s. &ldquo;A Tom Collins is easy,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s Gin and Tom Collins mix.&rdquo;
If I ever record an album, &ldquo;Gin and Tom Collins Mix&rdquo; is going into the shortlist of potential titles. Life was probably better when you could walk into a grocery store and find Collins mix next to the club soda. Anyhow, in current year we&rsquo;re barbarically forced to make a Tom Collins using the following ingredients:
2 oz gin 1 oz lemon juice (NOT lime juice) 1 oz simple syrup topped with club soda garnished with a lemon wedge, maybe a maraschino cherry too if you&rsquo;re feeling spicy It&rsquo;s hard to say why this is my go to. It&rsquo;s an anachronism in a world where the act of drinking alcohol itself is falling out of fashion with my Gen Z peers. In a landscape more commonly filled by Old Fashioneds and Espresso Martinis, it&rsquo;s often an inconvenience to the bartender to order this arcane highball. Many a apologetic shrug have I given to overworked, exasperated bartenders pulling out their phone to ask Google (or, god forbid, ChatGPT) how to make the old man bullshit I just ordered.
Maybe it&rsquo;s because the drink was once the subject of a sort of &ldquo;viral prank&rdquo; in 1874. It went something like this:
&ldquo;Hey, have you heard of Tom Collins?&rdquo;
&ldquo;No. Who is that?&rdquo;
&ldquo;He&rsquo;s in that bar talking about you.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What the heck, I&rsquo;d better take fisticuffs to that rapscallion.&rdquo;
The latter gentlemen would then enter the bar inquiring about Tom Collins, only to be served the drink. Everyone would share a hearty guffaw before returning to work in the coal mines and dying an early death from black lung.
Maybe it tickles me that there is a family of Collins drinks. Replacing the gin with rum gives you a Ron Collins. Tequila gives you a Juan or Jose Collins. Whiskey will give you a John Collins. Maybe the drink is really good? It&rsquo;s pretty good, essentially a bubbly alcoholic lemonade. Very crisp and refreshing at the end of a long day. If we&rsquo;re being real though, a whiskey sour is probably better.
Unfortunately, there&rsquo;s no whimsical answer here. It was one of the first drinks I ordered when I came of age (probably because it had a neat name), and it was inoffensive enough that it led to a habit that persists to this day. One of the lessons I&rsquo;ve learned in this life is that the subject of &ldquo;favorites&rdquo; or &ldquo;best&rdquo; usually comes down to momentary vibes rather than objective quality.
Still, in my book there&rsquo;s no higher honor than being good enough in most situations, and this cocktail fits that bill to a T. So go out and order a Tom Collins. If the bartender gets annoyed at you, tell them to blame Vinny.
